dus stimulated a long-lived tradition of Latin and vernacular "kisses", willfully repetitious and yet meticulously varied, which can tell us much about humanist poetics. This book offers a critical account of the Renaissance kiss-poem, using an abundance of vivid and often racy examples, many of them drawn from authors who are all but forgotten today. It shows that the genre had a sophisticated rationale and clear but flexible conventions. These include habits of irony, mood and structure that proved widely influential, and some slippery, self-conscious ways of dealing with masculine sexuality. Presenting new readings of English writers including Sidney, Shakespeare and Donne, the study also reminds us how important Neo-Latin writing was to the literary culture of early modern Britain. A number of well known texts are thus placed in a context unfamiliar to most modern scholars, in order to show how deftly their kisses engage with an international tradition of humanist poetry. Alex Wong is currently a Research Fellow in English literature at St John's College, University of Cambridge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aKissing in literature. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aClassical Reception.  aCultural history.  aDonne.  aEarly Modern Europe.  aEnglish literature.  aEuropean Renaissance.  aHumanist.  aMasculinity.  aNeo-Latin.  aRenaissance poetry.  aShakespeare.  aWomen in literature.  agender.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary history.  asexuality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744030240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440302